            "name": "backstory",
            "value": "Kai Littlebird\u2019s story began in the high desert of Flagstaff, Arizona, a place as mixed as his own heritage. The son of a reserved Japanese-American ceramicist and a spirited Navajo weaver, Kai grew up at the intersection of two distinct, artful cultures. His childhood was a sensory blend of his father\u2019s meticulously prepared ramen and his mother\u2019s hearty blue corn mush, flavors that quietly shaped his destiny.\n\nHe pursued a pragmatic degree in Hospitality and Event Management at Northern Arizona University, but his early career in hotel catering felt sterile and uninspired. The turning point came during a business trip to San Francisco in the late 90s. He catered a launch party for a dot-com startup and was mesmerized. Food wasn\u2019t just fuel; it was narrative, branding, and a centerpiece for connection. He saw his future and, within a year, had moved to the city.\n\nKai worked his way up through the competitive culinary scene, finding his niche not in the kitchen, but in designing the entire experience around it. Now, as a Corporate Culinary Experience Designer, he curates everything from themed pop-up lunches to elaborate food-centric galas for a major arts organization. He's the man who ensures an event *feels* as good as it tastes.\n\nNow 47, Kai\u2019s life is one of curated rhythm. He lives in a cozy Inner Richmond flat, its shelves lined with his father\u2019s pottery and his own amateur ceramics. His daily 2.8-mile bicycle commute to his SoMa office is a cherished ritual, a moment of peace before the creative storm of his workday. An amicable divorce a decade ago left him self-reliant but not solitary; his social life revolves around a tight-knit circle of food industry colleagues and friends from his ceramics studio.\n\nHis connection to San Francisco is deep, rooted in the city's appreciation for craft and multiculturalism. While he loves his career, Kai dreams of something smaller, more personal. He envisions opening an intimate supper club, a space where he can finally fuse his heritage on a plate\u2014serving dishes that speak of both the Arizona desert and the shores of Japan, telling his own unique story one course at a time."
        },
        {
            "@type": "PropertyValue",
            "name": "reveries",
            "value": "1.\nHe was 28, standing in the back of a cavernous SoMa warehouse. The air throbbed with trip-hop music and the electric buzz of a dot-com launch. He watched as venture capitalists raved over lamb chops with rosemary smoke captured under glass bells. It wasn't catering; it was theater. In that moment, the sterile buffets of his past evaporated. Food wasn't just sustenance, it was the story itself. He knew then he wouldn't be going back to Arizona. That night, San Francisco chose him.\n\n2.\nAt 16, he sat beside his father, not at the potter\u2019s wheel, but at the kitchen table. His father, silent as ever, slid a bowl of ramen towards him. \u201cTaste the shoyu,\u201d he\u2019d said, one of his few instructions. \u201cIt waits. It changes. Like the clay.\u201d Kai understood. Patience wasn\u2019t passive; it was an active ingredient, essential for both a perfect broth and a centered pot. That lesson in quiet transformation became the bedrock of his own craft, both in the kitchen and at the wheel.\n\n3.\nThe gala for the Arts Commission was his first major solo project. He\u2019d obsessed over every detail, from the edible flower placement to the specific hue of the lighting. Near the end of the night, he saw a notoriously stoic board member close her eyes, savoring a spoonful of chilled avocado soup from a ceramic cup he\u2019d personally selected. Her brief, peaceful smile was more validating than any applause. He hadn\u2019t just fed them; he had given them a moment of curated joy.\n\n4.\nThe day the divorce was finalized, he biked home to his new, empty apartment in the Inner Richmond. The climb up the hill burned in his legs, a physical echo of the ache in his chest. As he crested the peak, the fog rolled in, blanketing the city in a soft, quiet gray. He wasn't running from a life that had ended but pedaling toward a new kind of self-reliance. That daily commute became his ritual, a moving meditation on rebuilding piece by piece.\n\n5.\nJust last year, late one Tuesday in his ceramics studio, he held a freshly glazed bowl. It was imperfect, its shape subtly echoing both Pueblo pottery and Japanese wabi-sabi. In its curve, he suddenly envisioned not just a dish, but a whole menu: smoked trout on a bed of wild rice, alongside a tsukemono of pickled yucca blossom. It was the first time his two worlds felt not just connected, but fused. The supper club wasn't a dream anymore; it was a recipe he finally knew how to write."
